{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17642550","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17642550"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:41:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:41:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17951"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17951","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17951"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10665"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73007"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10665","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10665"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17951"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58478"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4899"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7272"},{"type":"tags","id":"7276"},{"type":"tags","id":"7294"},{"type":"tags","id":"11250"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24844"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24849"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73007","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73007"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following muscles is the intra-articular disc of the temporomandibular joint attached to?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Temporalis","Lateral pterygoid","Medial pterygoid","Hypoglossus","Masseter"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe intra-articular disc of the temporomandibular joint is attached to the \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral pterygoid\u003C/strong\u003E muscle. This muscle is responsible for the protrusion and lateral movement of the mandible. The attachment of the disc to the lateral pterygoid allows for coordinated movement of the disc and the condyle during jaw movements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etemporalis\u003C/strong\u003E muscle is involved in elevating and retracting the mandible but does not attach to the intra-articular disc.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial pterygoid\u003C/strong\u003E muscle assists in elevating the mandible and is not connected to the disc.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypoglossus\u003C/strong\u003E muscle is involved in tongue movement and has no role in the temporomandibular joint.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emasseter\u003C/strong\u003E muscle is a major muscle of mastication that elevates the mandible but does not attach to the intra-articular disc.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The intra-articular disc of the temporomandibular joint is attached to the lateral pterygoid muscle.","The lateral pterygoid muscle plays a role in the movement of the temporomandibular joint.","Understanding the anatomy of the temporomandibular joint is crucial for diagnosing and managing joint disorders."],"references":["Singh, V. (2023). Textbook of Anatomy-Head, Neck and Brain, Volume III-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Patestas, M. A., \u0026 Gartner, L. P. (2016). A textbook of neuroanatomy. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Patel, C. R., Fernandez-Miranda, J. C., Wang, W. H., \u0026 Wang, E. W. (2016). Skull Base Anatomy. Otolaryngologic clinics of North America, 49(1), 9\u201320. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.otc.2015.09.001","Anderson, B. W., Kortz, M. W., Black, A. C., \u0026 Al Kharazi, K. A. (2023). Anatomy, Head and Neck, Skull. In StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemR